5000|$|I.A. Richards' {{paternity}} of the New Criticism is in {{two books}} of critical theory, The Principles of Literary Criticism (1924) and Practical Criticism (1929). The first book, The Principles of Literary Criticism, discusses {{the subjects of}} [...] form, value, rhythm, <b>coenesthesia</b> (awareness of inhabiting one's body, caused by stimuli from various organs), literary infectiousness, allusiveness, divergent readings, and belief. The second book, Practical Criticism (1929), is an empirical study of inferior response to a literary text.|$|E

